    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-10-04T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-10-04T18:00:00-05:00" n="567"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d567">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">700.00(S)/10–450: Circular telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Certain <gloss type="to">Diplomatic Offices</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d567fn1">At Arab capitals and Tel Aviv.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-10-04T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 4, 1950—6 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>(<gloss target="#t_infotel1">Infotel</gloss>). <gloss target="#t_USUN1"
                        >USUN</gloss> reports that after expressing hope US wld support Arab
                    position in <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> on alleged Israeli aggression
                    against Jordan, member Iraqi Del<note n="2" xml:id="d567fn2">Fadhil
                        Jamali.</note> stated wld be good if <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> wld
                    impose on Arabs and Israel solution of Pal problem. He added that Arabs wld not
                    like it, but wld simply have to take it, and that, provided <gloss
                        target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>-imposed solution fair and equitable, he cld see
                    no other way achieving real peace. Meanwhile, Bunche<note n="3" xml:id="d567fn3"
                        >Ralph J. Bunche, former Acting United Nations Mediator in Palestine.</note>
                    told USGADel he thought Jordan made mistake in agreeing Yarmuk line. He doubted
                    forgery involved and thought more likely Jordanians taken in by more skillful
                    negotiators. Bunche felt, however, Jordan had good claim to terr in question on
                    basis equity, since never been intended that armistice negots shld involve
                    anything but Pal terr. He thought <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> shld refer
                    question back to <gloss target="#t_MAC1">MAC</gloss> in first instance.<note
                        n="4" xml:id="d567fn4">The information in this circular telegram is based on
                        telegram 647, October 4, from New York (310.5/10–450).</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Webb</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
